05841nam a22008535i 9780814733110DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20092009nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780814733110  a(DE-B1597)547312  a(OCoLC)779828095  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBM729.W6bW658 2016 7aREL0400002bisacsh04a296.08222300aWomen and Judaism :bNew Insights and Scholarship /ced. by Frederick E. Greenspahn. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJewish Studies in the Twenty-First Century ;v500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Four Approaches to Women and the Jewish Experience -- tPart I Classical Tradition -- t1 Jewish Feminist Approaches to the Bible -- t2 Women and Torah Study in Aggadah -- t3 Women and Jewish Law -- t4 Women in Medieval Jewish Societies -- t5 The Mystical Spirituality of Eastern European Jewish Women -- t6 How Central European Jewish Women Confronted Modernity -- tPart III Contemporary Life -- t7 Women and American Judaism -- t8 Women’s Transformations of Contemporary Jewish Life -- tPart IV Literature -- t9 Women in Jewish American Literature -- t10 Text, Nation, and Gender in Israeli Women’s Fiction -- tEpilogue: Women and Judaism: From Invisibility to Integration -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough women constitute half of the Jewish population and have always played essential roles in ensuring Jewish continuity and the preservation of Jewish beliefs and values, only recently have their contributions and achievements received sustained scholarly attention. Scholars have begun to investigate Jewish women’s domestic, economic, intellectual, spiritual, and creative roles in Jewish life from biblical times to the present. Yet little of this important work has filtered down beyond specialists in their respective academic fields. Women and Judaism brings the broad new insights they have uncovered to the world.Women and Judaism communicates this research to a wider public of students and educated readers outside of the academy by presenting accessible and engaging chapters written by key senior scholars that introduce the reader to different aspects of women and Judaism. The contributors discuss feminist approaches to Jewish law and Torah study, the spirituality of Eastern European Jewish women, Jewish women in American literature, and many other issues.Contributors: Nehama Aschkenasy, Judith R. Baskin, Sylvia Barack Fishman, Harriet Pass Freidenreich, Esther Fuchs, Judith Hauptman, Sara R. Horowitz, Renée Levine, Pamela S. Nadell, and Dvora Weisberg.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aFeminismxReligious aspectsxJudaism. 0aJewish literaturexWomen authors. 0aJewish women in literature. 0aJewish womenxHistory. 0aJewish womenxReligious life. 0aWomen in Judaism. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / General.2bisacsh1 aAschkenasy, Nehama, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaskin, Judith R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFishman, Sylvia Barack, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFreidenreich, Harriet Pass, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuchs, Esther, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenspahn, Frederick E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenspahn, Frederick E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHauptman, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorowitz, Sara R., econtributor.4c